{"abstract":"The dominant sequence transduction models are based on complex recurrent or convolutional neural networks that include an encoder and a decoder. The best performing models also connect the encoder and decoder through an attention mechanism. We propose a new simple network architecture, the Transformer, based solely on attention mechanisms, dispensing with recurrence and convolutions entirely. Experiments on two machine translation tasks show these models to be superior in quality while being more parallelizable and requiring significantly less time to train. Our model achieves 28.4 BLEU on the WMT 2014 English-to-German translation task, improving over the existing best results, including ensembles, by over 2 BLEU. On the WMT 2014 English-to-French translation task, our model establishes a new single-model state-of-the-art BLEU score of 41.0 after training for 3.5 days on eight GPUs, a small fraction of the training costs of the best models from the literature.","authors":["Ashish Vaswani","Noam Shazeer","Niki Parmar","Jakob Uszkoreit","Llion Jones","Aidan N. Gomez","Łukasz Kaiser","Illia Polosukhin"],"detailed_summary":"This seminal paper introduces the Transformer, a novel network architecture for sequence transduction tasks that completely avoids the use of recurrence and convolutions, which were dominant in the field. The authors identify the inherent sequential nature of Recurrent Neural Networks (RNNs) as a major bottleneck for parallelization and a hindrance to learning long-range dependencies in data. To address this, they propose a model built entirely on attention mechanisms, specifically multi-head self-attention, within an encoder-decoder structure. The architecture allows the model to process all input tokens simultaneously and draw global dependencies between them, using positional encodings to retain information about the sequence order. The paper validates this approach on two machine translation tasks (WMT 2014 English-to-German and English-to-French), demonstrating that the Transformer not only achieves superior translation quality, setting new state-of-the-art BLEU scores, but also trains significantly faster due to its high degree of parallelizability, thereby establishing a new and highly influential standard for sequence modeling.","isPublic":true,"journalName":"31st Conference on Neural Information Processing Systems (NIPS 2017)","keywords":["Transformer","attention mechanism","self-attention","sequence transduction","machine translation","encoder-decoder"],"level":"info","message":"Metadata parsed successfully:","paperLink":"","publication_date":"2017-01-01T00:00:00.000Z","service":"research-companion-api","timestamp":"2025-08-06 18:09:45","title":"Attention Is All You Need"}
