{"level":"info","message":"Starting paper upload: NIPS-2017-attention-is-all-you-need-Paper.pdf by user: 6891da7a12b01d9d8d137175 (source: file)","service":"research-companion-api","timestamp":"2025-08-07 09:07:45"}
{"abstract":"The dominant sequence transduction models are based on complex recurrent or convolutional neural networks that include an encoder and a decoder. The best performing models also connect the encoder and decoder through an attention mechanism. We propose a new simple network architecture, the Transformer, based solely on attention mechanisms, dispensing with recurrence and convolutions entirely. Experiments on two machine translation tasks show these models to be superior in quality while being more parallelizable and requiring significantly less time to train. Our model achieves 28.4 BLEU on the WMT 2014 English-to-German translation task, improving over the existing best results, including ensembles, by over 2 BLEU. On the WMT 2014 English-to-French translation task, our model establishes a new single-model state-of-the-art BLEU score of 41.0 after training for 3.5 days on eight GPUs, a small fraction of the training costs of the best models from the literature.","authors":["Ashish Vaswani","Noam Shazeer","Niki Parmar","Jakob Uszkoreit","Llion Jones","Aidan N. Gomez","Łukasz Kaiser","Illia Polosukhin"],"detailed_summary":"This paper addresses the limitations of dominant sequence transduction models, such as Recurrent Neural Networks (RNNs) and Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM) networks, whose inherently sequential nature precludes parallelization and makes it difficult to learn long-range dependencies. The primary objective was to design a new network architecture that dispenses with recurrence and convolutions entirely, relying solely on an attention mechanism to achieve superior performance, greater parallelization, and significantly reduced training times.\n\nThe authors propose the Transformer, a novel encoder-decoder architecture. The encoder is a stack of six identical layers, where each layer consists of a multi-head self-attention sub-layer and a position-wise, fully connected feed-forward network. The decoder has a similar stack of six layers but inserts a third sub-layer that performs multi-head attention over the output of the encoder. To retain positional information in the absence of recurrence, the model adds 'positional encodings' to the input embeddings. The core innovation is 'Multi-Head Attention', which allows the model to jointly attend to information from different representational subspaces. Specifically, the paper uses 'Scaled Dot-Product Attention' in parallel across eight 'heads', concatenating their outputs. Residual connections and layer normalization are applied around each sub-layer to facilitate training of this deep architecture.\n\nThe Transformer model was evaluated on the WMT 2014 English-to-German and English-to-French machine translation tasks. The results were groundbreaking. The model achieved a BLEU score of 28.4 on the English-to-German task, outperforming the existing best models by over 2 BLEU points. On the English-to-French task, it established a new single-model state-of-the-art BLEU score of 41.0. Critically, these results were achieved with significantly less training time; the model was trained for only 3.5 days on eight GPUs, a small fraction of the training costs of previous top-performing models.\n\nThe significance of these findings is profound. The paper demonstrates that a simpler architecture based purely on attention can not only match but significantly outperform complex recurrent models. This challenged the prevailing view that recurrence was indispensable for sequence modeling. The main contributions of this work are the introduction of the Transformer architecture, the proposal of the multi-head attention mechanism, and the empirical demonstration of its state-of-the-art performance and training efficiency. This work fundamentally shifted the paradigm in sequence modeling and laid the groundwork for the development of modern large language models.","gemini_analysis":{"future_directions":[],"key_findings":["The Transformer architecture, based solely on attention, achieves state-of-the-art performance on machine translation tasks, surpassing previous models based on recurrent or convolutional networks.","On the WMT 2014 English-to-German translation task, the model achieved a BLEU score of 28.4, an improvement of over 2 BLEU points compared to the previous best results.","A new single-model state-of-the-art BLEU score of 41.0 was established on the WMT 2014 English-to-French translation task.","The model is significantly more parallelizable than recurrent architectures, which allows for a substantial reduction in training time. It reached SOTA performance after only 3.5 days of training on eight P100 GPUs.","Self-attention allows the model to learn long-range dependencies between input and output sequences with a constant number of operations, unlike the linear or logarithmic path lengths required by RNNs and some CNNs.","Multi-head attention is an effective mechanism that allows the model to jointly attend to information from different representation subspaces at different positions, which is more powerful than a single attention mechanism."],"limitations":["The computational and memory complexity of the self-attention mechanism is quadratic with respect to the sequence length (O(n^2)), making it inefficient for extremely long sequences.","The model's reliance on fixed or learned positional encodings to understand sequence order is a departure from the inherent sequential processing of RNNs, and the optimal method for encoding position is not fully explored.","The paper focuses exclusively on machine translation, and its performance on other types of sequence-to-sequence tasks is not evaluated in this work.","The paper mentions that averaging attention-weighted positions can reduce effective resolution, a problem counteracted by multi-head attention, but this trade-off might still pose a subtle limitation."],"methodology":"The paper introduces the Transformer, a novel network architecture for sequence transduction tasks that completely avoids recurrence and convolutions. It is an encoder-decoder model built upon stacked layers. Each layer in the encoder and decoder contains two main sub-layers: a multi-head self-attention mechanism and a position-wise fully connected feed-forward network. The decoder includes an additional attention layer that attends to the encoder's output. The model uses 'Scaled Dot-Product Attention' and 'Multi-Head Attention' (with h=8 heads) to capture dependencies regardless of their distance in the sequence. Since the model contains no inherent sequential structure, 'positional encodings' are added to the input embeddings to provide information about the order of tokens. The architecture also employs residual connections and layer normalization around each sub-layer. The model was evaluated on WMT 2014 English-to-German and English-to-French translation tasks, using the BLEU score as the primary metric.","research_area":"Natural Language Processing (Machine Translation) and Deep Learning Architectures","research_impact":"The paper has had a revolutionary impact on the field of Natural Language Processing and beyond. The Transformer architecture has become the de facto standard for sequence modeling, replacing RNNs and LSTMs in most state-of-the-art systems. It laid the foundation for subsequent large language models like BERT, GPT, T5, and others, which have driven massive advancements in NLP. The high degree of parallelization it enables has allowed for the training of unprecedentedly large models, fundamentally changing the scale of research in the field. Its core concepts, particularly self-attention, have been successfully adapted to other domains, including computer vision (Vision Transformers) and biology, demonstrating its versatility and profound influence on the broader machine learning landscape."},"isPublic":true,"journalName":"Conference on Neural Information Processing Systems (NIPS)","keywords":["Transformer","Attention Mechanism","Self-Attention","Sequence Transduction","Machine Translation","Encoder-Decoder Architecture","Neural Networks","Parallelization","Natural Language Processing"],"level":"info","message":"Metadata parsed successfully:","paperLink":"","publication_date":"2017-12-04T00:00:00.000Z","service":"research-companion-api","timestamp":"2025-08-07 09:07:45","title":"Attention Is All You Need"}
